Package ru.nsu.fit.smolyakov.graph

Class AbstractGraph<V>

java.lang.Object
ru.nsu.fit.smolyakov.graph.AbstractGraph<V>
Direct Known Subclasses:
AdjacencyMatrixGraph, IncidentListGraph
public abstract class AbstractGraph<V> extends Object
This class provides a skeletal implementation of the graph data structure to minimize the effort required to implement it.

Multigraphs are not supported! If a user attempts to use addEdge(V,V,int) with multiple edges, it will return false and insert one that occurs first.

This abstract class specification admits inherited classes to be immutable. It means that clear(), addVertex(V), addEdge(V,V,int), reweightEdge(V,V,int), removeVertex(V), removeEdge(V,V) and all methods connected to them may throw UnsupportedOperationException.

    • toIncidentList

      public IncidentListGraph<V> toIncidentList()
      Turns this AbstractGraph into IncidentListGraph, as in general it's the most asymptotically profitable.

      Default implementation creates an empty instance of incident list graph and than uses it as a parameter for switchGraphRepresentation(ru.nsu.fit.smolyakov.graph.AbstractGraph<V>).

      Returns:
      this graph, represented as an incident list
      See Also:
      • IncidentListGraph

    • switchGraphRepresentation

      public AbstractGraph<V> switchGraphRepresentation(AbstractGraph<V> graph)
      Turns this AbstractGraph into specified AbstractGraph.

      In default implementation specified graph will be cleared by clear() method, respectively be sure it's correct one. It's also very unoptimised, so it's highly recommended to override that.

      Parameters:
      graph - presentation to be turned into
      Returns:
      this graph, represented as specified by graph
      Throws:
      UnsupportedOperationException - if clear(), addVertex(V) or addEdge(V,V,int) operations are not supported by the specified graph.

    • getEdgeWeight

      public OptionalInt getEdgeWeight(V from, V to)
      Returns a weight of an edge connected to specified vertices. If this edge doesn't exist, this method does nothing and returns OptionalInt.empty().

      Default implementation uses a getEdge(V,V), so it might be not very effective with some graph presentation methods.

      Parameters:
      from - a vertex a specified edge comes from
      to - a vertex a specified edge comes to
      Returns:
      OptionalInt of old weight if an edge between specified vertices exists, OptionalInt.empty() otherwise

    • reweightEdge

      public OptionalInt reweightEdge(V from, V to, int newWeight)
      Changes edge's weight to a specified one (optional operation). If edge doesn't exist, this method does nothing and returns OptionalInt.empty().

      Default implementation uses a composition of addEdge(V,V,int) and removeEdge(V,V), so it might be not very effective with some graph presentation methods.

      Parameters:
      from - a vertex a specified edge comes from
      to - a vertex a specified edge comes to
      newWeight - a new weight of an edge
      Returns:
      OptionalInt of old weight if an edge between specified vertices exists, OptionalInt.empty() otherwise
      Throws:
      UnsupportedOperationException - if this operation is not supported by this graph

    • findShortestPaths

      public Map<V,Integer> findShortestPaths(V s)
      Implements Dijkstra shortest paths algorithm. As it uses priority queue to always keep current shortest paths naturally sorted, this implementation is asymtotically effective. Edges with negative weights are not allowed!
      Parameters:
      s - a vertex to find shortest paths from
      Returns:
      a map containing shortest paths from s vertex to all.
      Throws:
      IllegalStateException - if one of edges has negative weight
      See Also:
      • Map
      • PriorityQueue
